## Step 1: Multiply the first equation by $xy$ to clear the fractions.
\begin{align*}
y + x &= 5xy
\end{align*}
## Step 2: Substitute $y + x = 5xy$ into the second equation.
\begin{align*}
3xy + (5xy) &= 4
\end{align*}
## Step 3: Simplify the equation to solve for $xy$.
\begin{align*}
8xy &= 4\\
\Rightarrow \qquad xy &= \frac{4}{8} = \frac{1}{2}
\end{align*}
## Step 4: Substitute $xy=\frac{1}{2}$ back into $y + x = 5xy$ to get $y + x = 5\cdot\frac{1}{2}$.
\begin{align*}
y + x &= \frac{5}{2}
\end{align*}
## Step 5: Compute $x^2y+xy^2$.
\begin{align*}
x^2y+xy^2&=xy(x+y)\\
&=\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{5}{2}\right)\\
&=\frac{5}{4}
\end{align*}
## Step 6
\begin{align*}
x^2y+xy^2&=xy(x+y)\\
&=xy\left(5xy\right)\\
&=5x^2y^2
\end{align*}
## Step 7
\begin{align*}
5x^2y^2&=5\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2\\
&=5\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)\\
&=\frac{5}{4}
\end{align*}
## Step 8
\begin{align*}
x^2y^2&=\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2\\
&=\frac{1}{4}
\end{align*}
## Step 9
\begin{align*}
5x^2y^2&=5\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)\\
&=\frac{5}{4}
\end{align*}
## Step 10
\begin{align*}
x^2y+xy^2&=xy(x+y)\\
&=xy\left(\frac{5}{2}\right)\\
&=\frac{5}{2}xy
\end{align*}

